# What a compiler does

You type source. Something emits `<p>Hello, Priya!</p>`. Between those two facts sits a long chain of careful transformations, each one slightly less human and slightly more machine-shaped than the last.

People often shrink that chain to a slogan: "the compiler turns code into machine instructions." That slogan fails the greeting project before lunch. The page may never touch native machine code. It may still need tokens, types, control-flow graphs, link plans and a builder that writes HTML. The work still deserves the word *compiler*.

## Meaning versus representation

**Source meaning** answers "what did the author intend under the language rules?"

**Target representation** answers "what concrete form will some host execute or display?"

**Transformation** answers "how do we move from one to the other without losing the meaning we care about?"

The project tree enters as authored text:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
compiler_walkthrough/
├── config.bst
└── src/
    ├── #page.bst
    └── greeting.bst
]

Those files hold characters on disk. They do not yet hold a typed call graph, a borrow fact or a Wasm export. Meaning arrives only when a stage applies language rules and records the result in a structure later stages trust.

A seed is not a vine. The same genetic plan can become different adult forms under different conditions, yet the plan stays one plan. Source meaning is the plan. Target code is the grown plant in a particular climate: browser JavaScript, Wasm, HTML shell. Compilers live in the gap between seed and stand of growth.

**Diagram placeholder:** One seed plan becomes different grown forms while keeping the same meaning

